        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "Great question — this distinction gets at the heart of what happens *inside* a language model versus at its *surface*. Let's unpack it.\n\n## Token Substrate (recap)\n\nThe **token substrate** is the **discrete, symbolic layer** at the model's input and output:\n\n- Made of tokens drawn from a finite vocabulary.\n- Human-interpretable (you can read them).\n- The interface where text enters and leaves the model.\n- Static: a token's identity doesn't change based on context.\n\n## Latent Representation / Hidden States\n\nA **latent representation** (or **hidden state**) is the **internal, continuous vector** a model computes at each layer as it processes input:\n\n- **Continuous and high-dimensional**: vectors in ℝⁿ (e.g., 4096-d).\n- **Contextual**: the same token gets *different* hidden states depending on surrounding tokens.\n- **Layered**: every transformer layer produces its own hidden state for each position.\n- **Not directly human-readable**: meaning is distributed across dimensions.\n- **Dynamic**: shaped by attention to all other tokens in the context.\n\nHidden states are where the model's \"thinking\" actually happens.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Token Substrate | Hidden States / Latents |\n|---|---|---|\n| Nature | Discrete symbols | Continuous vectors |\n| Location | Input/output interface | Internal layers |\n| Context-sensitive? | No (fixed identity) | Yes (depends on neighbors) |\n| Human-readable? | Yes | No (opaque) |\n| Count per token | One ID | One vector *per layer* |\n| Role | What the model reads/writes | How the model represents meaning mid-computation |\n\n## How They Relate to Embeddings\n\nIt's worth distinguishing **embeddings** from **hidden states**, since they're often confused:\n\n- **Embedding**: the *initial* vector for a token, looked up from a static table — the same regardless of context.\n- **Hidden state**: the *evolving* vector at each layer, shaped by attention over the whole context. Layer 0 ≈ embedding; layer N = a deeply contextualized representation.\n\nSo hidden states are what embeddings *become* as they flow through the model.\n\n## Analogy\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the **words on a page** — fixed, discrete, readable.\n- The **embedding space** is like a **dictionary lookup** — each word has a default meaning-vector.\n- The **hidden states** are like the **thoughts in a reader's mind** as they read — fluid, contextual, shaped by everything that came before, and not directly observable.\n\nThe same word \"bank\" appears identically on the page (substrate), gets the same dictionary entry (embedding), but evokes very different mental representations (hidden states) in \"river bank\" vs. \"savings bank.\"\n\n## How They Interact in the Pipeline\n\n```\nText\n  ↓ tokenization\nTokens (substrate)         ← discrete, symbolic\n  ↓ embedding lookup\nInitial vectors             ← static, context-free\n  ↓ layer 1 (attention + FFN)\nHidden state at layer 1     ← contextualized\n  ↓ layer 2\nHidden state at layer 2     ← more abstracted\n  ↓ ... many layers ...\nFinal hidden state          ← rich, task-relevant representation\n  ↓ unembedding (projection)\nToken probabilities\n  ↓ sampling\nOutput token (substrate)    ← back to discrete symbols\n```\n\nThe model spends almost all its computation in the hidden-state realm. The token substrate is just the **entry and exit doors**; the latents are the **rooms inside the building**.\n\n## Why the Distinction Matters\n\n1. **Interpretability research** focuses heavily on hidden states — probing them to understand what the model \"knows\" or \"represents\" internally.\n2. **Activation steering and feature extraction** (e.g., sparse autoencoders, probing classifiers) operate on hidden states, not tokens.\n3. **The token substrate is lossy**: rich latent meaning has to be compressed back into discrete tokens at output, which is why models sometimes \"know\" more than they can cleanly say.\n4. **Capability emerges in the latents**: reasoning, abstraction, and feature composition happen in hidden-state space — the substrate just delivers and receives.\n\n## Quick Summary of the Whole Stack\n\n- **Token substrate** = the *symbols* (discrete, surface-level).\n- **Embedding space** = the *static geometry* of those symbols (continuous, context-free).\n- **Hidden states / latents** = the *dynamic, contextual representations* the model computes layer by layer (continuous, context-sensitive, where reasoning lives).\n- **Context window** = the *span* of substrate tokens that get lifted into latent space together.\n\nWant to go deeper into how hidden states evolve across layers, or into interpretability techniques that try to \"read\" them?",
